# CV / Resume Project — Maintenance Rules

## Project structure and source of truth

- **generate-resume.md** — Main content source: contact, summary, experience, skills, projects, education, etc. Used to generate `resume.html` via Pandoc.
- **resume.html** — HTML resume (generated from `generate-resume.md` or kept in sync manually). Styled with `resume-template.css`.
- **index.html** — Public site: hero, about, experience timeline, skills grid, projects, testimonials, contact. Must reflect the same facts as the resume.
- **generate-pdf.sh** — Builds PDF from `generate-resume.md` → `resume.html` (Pandoc) then HTML → PDF (Prince). Output e.g. `puzik-cv.pdf`.

## Keeping files in sync

1. **Skills** — The same set of skills with the same descriptions must appear in all three:
   - `generate-resume.md` (sections: Frontend, Backend, DevOps & Tools, Analytics & Experimentation, AI & Emerging Technologies, Databases & Storage)
   - `resume.html` (same section titles and list items)
   - `index.html` (skill categories and skill items; names may include short descriptions in parentheses)

2. **When adding, removing, or editing a skill:**
   - Update `generate-resume.md` first (canonical list and wording).
   - Update `resume.html` to match (same categories and items).
   - Update `index.html`: same categories, same items; keep `skill-name` + `skill-level` and optional short description in the name.

3. **Experience (jobs):** Keep company, period, role, description, and technologies identical across `generate-resume.md`, `resume.html`, and the experience/timeline block in `index.html`.

4. **Projects, contact, summary:** Any change in one place must be reflected in the other two where that content exists.

5. **Regenerating resume/PDF:** After editing `generate-resume.md`, run `./generate-pdf.sh` to refresh `resume.html` and the PDF. If `resume.html` is edited by hand (e.g. extra sections not in Markdown), sync those edits back into `generate-resume.md` or document the exception.

## Private files and .gitignore

- **Private files** (notes, drafts, personal data, local-only content) must live in a folder that is ignored by Git.
- In `.gitignore`, ensure an entry for that folder exists (e.g. `private/` or `_private/`). Do not commit the contents of that folder.
- Do not reference or copy content from the private folder into `resume.html`, `index.html`, or `generate-resume.md` unless the user explicitly asks.

## Skill development strategy (for you only)

**Do not add this section or its content to resume.html, index.html, or generate-resume.md.** It is only for your and the AI’s context when discussing priorities.

- Prioritise depth in 2–3 core areas (e.g. Vue/Laravel + AI/agents + payments or data) rather than listing many shallow skills.
- Add a new skill to the three files only when you have real project or learning evidence (e.g. shipped feature, course, pet project).
- Once per quarter: review the skills list, remove obsolete or weak items, tighten descriptions, align level (Expert/Advanced/Intermediate/Learning) with actual use.
- Keep “Learning” and “Intermediate” to a small number so the resume stays credible; prefer “Advanced” for things you use regularly in production.

When the user asks to “add a skill” or “update skills,” apply the sync rules above and do not inject the strategy text into any project file.
